05162nam a22008175i 9780823298754DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232987547 a10.1515/97808232987542doi  a(DE-B1597)623917  a(OCoLC)1286431462  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0270002bisacsh1 aTrumbull, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Life to Survival :bDerrida, Freud, and the Future of Deconstruction /cRobert Trumbull. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Derrida, Freud, and the Future of Deconstruction -- t1 From Grammatology to Life Death -- t2 Interrogating the Death Drive -- t3 Survival as Autoimmunity -- t4 Mortality and Normativity -- t5 Sovereignty, Cruelty, and the Death Penalty -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContemporary continental thought is marked by a move away from the “linguistic turn” in twentieth-century European philosophy, as new materialisms and ontologies seek to leave behind the thinking of language central to poststructuralism as it has been traditionally understood. At the same time, biopolitical philosophy has brought critical attention to the question of life, examining new formations of life and death. Within this broader turn, Derridean deconstruction, with its apparent focus on language, writing, and textuality, is generally set aside.This book, by contrast, shows the continued relevance of deconstruction for contemporary thought’s engagement with resolutely material issues and with matters of life and the living. Trumbull elaborates Derrida’s thinking of life across his work, specifically his recasting of life as “life death,” and in turn, survival or living on. Derrida’s activation of Freud, Trumbull shows, is central to this problematic and its consequences, especially deconstruction’s ethical and political possibilities. The book traces how Derrida’s early treatment of Freud and his mobilization of Freud’s death drive allow us to grasp the deconstructive thought of life as constitutively exposed to death, the logic subsequently rearticulated in the notion of survival. Derrida’s recasting of life as survival, Trumbull demonstrates, allows deconstruction to destabilize inherited understandings of life, death, and the political, including the dominant configurations of sovereignty and the death penalty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDeconstruction. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh  aContinental philosophy.  aJacques Derrida.  aLa vie la mort.  aSigmund Freud.  adeath drive.  adeath penalty.  adeconstruction.  aethics and politics.  alife death.  asovereignty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2022 Englishz978311099276208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2022z9783110992755oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075166640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823298754?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823298754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823298754/original  a978-3-11-075166-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099276-2  EBOOK